  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical buzzword—it's a real barrier I've seen firsthand in my own life and the lives of my community. Growing up in a neighborhood where many of my peers didn't have the same opportunities to explore science or engineering, I remember feeling nervous about getting the 'right' answers in class because I didn't want to confirm the stereotype that 'you can't be good at math.' That anxiety can make you feel like you're failing before you even start. As a mechanic, I know how important it is to trust your instincts and focus on the problem at hand, but when you're worried about being labeled or judged, it's hard to do that effectively. I've seen this dynamic play out in my shop: when someone is nervous about their technical skills, they might avoid challenging tasks, which can slow down progress and limit their potential. Addressing stereotype threat requires practical, community-driven approaches. For example, creating mentorship programs that pair students with local professionals like myself could help build confidence and show that STEM isn't just for a select few. It's also important to acknowledge the emotional toll this can have—many people feel isolated or discouraged, which can lead to depression, as I've experienced. The solution isn't about changing the system overnight but about fostering environments where people feel safe to make mistakes and learn from them. In my community, we could start small by organizing workshops that focus on hands-on problem-solving, not just theory. This way, we can address the root of the issue without overwhelming anyone. Ultimately, if we want to see more people succeed in STEM, we need to create spaces where everyone feels valued and capable, not just 'the right' ones.",
